				<section>
					<h2 class="mytitle">Modified Unilateral Approach for Ventrally Located Spinal Tumors</h2>
					<h2 class="my-institute">Department of Neurological Surgery<br>Tokai University, Kanagawa, Japan</h2>
					<h2 class="authors">Han Soo Chang, M.D., Yumetaro Sakakibara, M.D.,<br>Fumiya Sano, M.D., Takatoshi Sorimachi, M.D.</h2>
				</section>
				<section>
					<h3>Surgery for Ventrally Located Spinal Tumors</h3>
					<img class="r-stretch" src="images/ventral-tumor.png"/>
					<aside class="notes">
						Ventrally located spinal tumors poses a challenge to spinal surgeons. The tumor must be removed without damaging the cord through excessive retraction.
					</aside>
				</section>
				<section>
					<h3>Problem of the Conventional Unilateral Approach</h3>
					<img class="r-stretch" src="images/viewing_angle_standard.png"/>
					<aside class="notes">
						The unilateral approach is less invasive, but the viewing angle is limited by the muscles, skin, and retractor blades.
					</aside>
				</section>
				<section>
					<h2>Modified Unilateral Approach</h2>
					<aside class="notes">
						We attempted to overcome this problem with a simple modification of the unilateral approach.
					</aside>
				</section>
				<section>
					<h3>Scheme of Surgical Technique</h3>
					<img class="r-stretch" src="images/scheme_of_technique.jpg"/>
					<aside class="notes">
						We make a horizontal skin incision instead of a midline one, and expose the unilateral laminae. Then, we make an incision only on the fascia, which makes the retraction of muscles easier. We then apply a pair of retractors in the longitudinal direction and make a small incision on the medial part of the multifidus muscle as needed. This procedure adds a wide lateral space to the conventional unilateral approach.
					</aside>
				</section>
				<section>
                    <h3>Opening for a C8 schwannoma case</h3>
                    <video data-autoplay src="images/oyamada_opening.mp4"></video>
					<aside class="notes">
						This video shows an opening for a C8 schwannoma case. We begin by making a horizontal skin incision and exposing the unilateral laminae. Following this, we make an incision on the superficial fascia, which aids in the longitudinal retraction of the muscle. Ultimately, we make a small incision on the medial part of the multifidus muscle, as necessary, to complete the exposure.
					</aside>
                </section>
				<section>
					<h3>Benefit of Modified Unilateral Approach</h3>
					<img class="r-stretch" src="images/viewing_angles.png"/>
					<aside class="notes">
						Therefore, the modified unilateral approach offers an additional lateral viewing angle and creates extra space for the lateral insertion of instruments.
					</aside>
				</section>
				<section>
					<h3>Benefit of Modified Unilateral Approach</h3>
					<div class="two-columns">
						<div class="half">
							<figure>
								<img src="images/araki_insertion_2.png"/>
								<figcaption>Conventional Unilateral</figcaption>
							</figure>
						</div>
						<div class="half">
							<figure>
								<img src="images/佐藤正_wide_view.png"/>
								<figcaption>Modified Unilateral</figcaption>
							</figure>
						</div>
					</div>
					<aside class="notes">
						Please compare the limited lateral space provided by the conventional unilateral approach with the expanded lateral space achieved through the modified unilateral approach.
					</aside>
				</section>
				<section>
					<h3>Dissection of a Ventrally Located Cavernoma</h3>
					<video data-autoplay src="images/satoh_insertion.mp4"></video>
					<aside class="notes">
						Using the modified unilateral approach, we can dissect a tumor from the ventral side of the spinal cord, benefiting from the additional lateral space provided.
					</aside>
				</section>
				<section>
					<h3>Case Series</h3>
					<img class="r-stretch" src="images/case_series.png"/>
					<aside class="notes">
						This table depicts a series of 15 cases where ventrally located spinal tumors were effectively managed using our modified unilateral approach. The extent of tumor resection was satisfactory in all instances. Importantly, we did not encounter any complications related to damage to the paraspinal muscles.
					</aside>
				</section>
				<section>
					<h3>Case 1. Thoracic Schwannoma</h3>
					<img class="r-stretch" src="images/hirota_tadashi.png"/>
					<aside class="notes">
						Here we have a case of a thoracic schwannoma. The spinal cord was located on the dorsal side of the tumor. Upon opening the dura, we found the tumor almost completely covered by the spinal cord. Despite this, we successfully leveraged the extra lateral space provided by our modified approach to completely remove the tumor through this limited gap. Please take note of the minimal damage to the paravertebral muscle in the postoperative MRI.
					</aside>
				</section>
